The $121 million sale of philanthropist Mica Ertegun=E2=80=99s prized Magri=
tte painting, considered by most to be the best of the 27 images the artist=
 made in his L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res series, was the dramatic hi=
ghlight of the November auction season in New York. But the announcement of=
 the sale also set up another drama, playing out six lots later, when a muc=
h smaller version of the same image, painted on paper, sold for $18.8 milli=
on=E2=80=94more than twice the previous record for a work on paper by the B=
elgian surrealist. In the end, the sale unfolded like clockwork, but it mas=
ked a carefully choreographed series of events that had taken place behind =
the scenes.

Prior to the announcement that Ertegun=E2=80=99s estate would be coming to =
market, art advisor Gabriela Palmieri knew that the big painting=E2=80=99s
sale would be a singular opportunity for her clients, whose family had owne=
d a version of the image painted on paper for more than 40 years, never sho=
wing it or even letting Magritte scholars know they had it. The collectors =
weren=E2=80=99t active sellers, but Palmieri convinced them the Ertegun sal=
e would set up a once-in-a-lifetime market opportunity. Of the 27 images Ma=
gritte made of the night-shrouded street under a daybright blue sky flecked=
 with picture-perfect clouds, 10 were painted on paper using opaque waterco=
lors called gouache. Ertegun owned the largest painting on canvas in privat=
e hands; Palmieri=E2=80=99s clients had the largest work on paper.

