If Rotter=E2=80=99s bidder, widely gossiped about and reported without cont=
radiction as billionaire Ken Griffin, was also the third-party guarantor, t=
he selling price was probably somewhere below the pro forma $121 million a =
non-guarantor would have paid. (Christie=E2=80=99s no longer reports net pr=
ices, as Sotheby=E2=80=99s continues to do.) Nevertheless, the value statem=
ent had been made. The top price for a Magritte had moved up by 50 percent =
in two and a half years, repricing almost everything underneath. A few lots=
 after the gouache of L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res, a slightly smalle=
r gouache of a different Magritte image, La recherche de l=E2=80=99absolu, =
estimated at $3 million, made $8.4 million with fees. By contrast, two othe=
r Magrittes owned by Ertegun, which sold at the beginning of her sale, only=
 made prices around the estimate levels.
There was no Magritte bidding bump before the big L=E2=80=99empire painting=
 sold. There was one after. Timing really is everything.

Christie=E2=80=99s had carefully placed the Ertegun L=E2=80=99empire des lu=
mi=C3=A8res as the last lot, a fitting crescendo to her dedicated sale, but=
 selling the gouache required an assist. The hope was that the underbidder =
on the large painting would switch to the smaller one, but bruised feelings=
 take a little time to get over, and Christie=E2=80=99s would have wanted a=
 little space for the impact of the big sale to sink in. Also, if the big p=
ainting sold to the guarantor in an anticlimactic moment, the change of sal=
e from Ertegun to various owners would act as a buffer, allowing bidders to=
 regroup and rebuild momentum.

In the end, there were five lots placed between the big Magritte and its li=
ttle brother, but the gouache was positioned right before Christie=E2=80=99=
s other big lot of the evening: Ed Ruscha=E2=80=99s Standard Station,
priced at $50 million but expected to be bid higher. In setting up the lot =
order, Christie=E2=80=99s both expressed its confidence in its ability to m=
arket both paintings and put all of its eggs into one high-risk basket. The=
 big Magritte had a belt-and-suspenders third-party guarantee, but the smal=
l Magritte and the Ruscha were being sold naked, as they say. Both the litt=
le Magritte and the big Ruscha had to sell well for Christie=E2=80=99s to c=
all the night a success=E2=80=94and make any money.

In the end, Christie=E2=80=99s didn=E2=80=99t have to worry. Close to a doz=
en different bidders chased the L=E2=80=99empire gouache. Bidding started i=
n the room for as little as $4.8 million, but quickly escalated in a relay =
race of bidding and counter-bidding. Max Carter, who had done so much to ca=
rry the ball on Palmieri=E2=80=99s consignment in-house, came in at $11 mil=
lion. There were still several bidders active at $14 million, but Li-Cohen=
=E2=80=94who=E2=80=99d come in at $12.5 million, presumably
representing the under bidder on the big empire painting=E2=80=94pushed to =
$15.5 million. Carter took one last shot, chopping his bid to $15.7 million=
, which signalled to Li-Cohen that $16 million would most likely take it. S=
he bid that=E2=80=A6 and won.

Art auctions rarely adhere to such a tightly choreographed and cinematic sc=
ript. Minutes before the sale, Michel Legrand=E2=80=99s theme to The Thomas=
 Crown Affair came over the sound system, in homage to a Magritte having be=
en the object of Crown=E2=80=99s larcenous obsession in the 1999 remake. Th=
e sale of the gouache provided the necessary subplot to bring the whole sto=
ry together.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

With all the hullabaloo around the auctions, I missed a chance to comment o=
n the FT=E2=80=99s fascinating lunch ( https://www.ft.com/content/9ed91396-=
d77a-4205-83b4-e97348d45749?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2=
F1%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F1%2F24%29&utm_med=
ium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )=
 with Nicholas Cullinan, the new head of the British Museum who formerly ra=
n London=E2=80=99s National Portrait Gallery and had been a curator of mode=
rn and contemporary art at the Met in New York before that. There are many =
issues bedeviling the British Museum=E2=80=94a scandal around stolen object=
s from the collection, a crumbling physical plant, questions about maintain=
ing a preeminent global institution on a budget paid for by a reduced regio=
nal power=E2=80=94but the most interesting
thing about the profile is Cullinan=E2=80=99s refreshing approach to proble=
ms.

The piece also cites his coup de gr=C3=A2ce at the NPG, where he saved an i=
mportant Joshua Reynolds painting for the British public by forging an alli=
ance with the Getty museum. He=E2=80=99s now applying that same approach to=
 the British Museum=E2=80=99s most famous possession, the statues from the =
Parthenon ( https://www.britishmuseum.org/about-us/british-museum-story/con=
tested-objects-collection/parthenon-sculptures?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+=
SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F1%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%=
2F1%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df=
6c60617da42abd12a ) also known as the Elgin Marbles.

With that, I will leave you until Tuesday.

