le of philanthropist <b>Mica</b> <b>Ertegun</b>=E2=80=99s prized <b>Magritt=
e</b> painting, considered by most to be the best of the 27 images the arti=
st made in his <i>L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res</i> series, was the dr=
amatic highlight of the November auction season in New York. But the announ=
cement of the sale also set up <i>another</i> drama, playing out six lots l=
ater, when a much smaller version of the same image, painted on paper, sold=
 for $18.8 million=E2=80=94more than twice the previous record for a work o=
n paper by the Belgian surrealist. In the end, the sale unfolded like clock=
work, but it masked a carefully choreographed series of events that had tak=
en place behind the scenes. <br/><br/>Prior to the announcement that Ertegu=
n=E2=80=99s estate would be coming to market, art advisor <b>Gabriela</b> <=
b>Palmieri</b> knew that the big painting=E2=80=99s
sale would be a singular opportunity for her clients, whose family had owne=
d a version of the image painted on paper for more than 40 years, never sho=
wing it or even letting Magritte scholars know they had it. The collectors =
weren=E2=80=99t active sellers, but Palmieri convinced them the Ertegun sal=
e would set up a once-in-a-lifetime market opportunity. Of the 27 images Ma=
gritte made of the night-shrouded street under a daybright blue sky flecked=
 with picture-perfect clouds, 10 were painted on paper using opaque waterco=
lors called gouache. Ertegun owned the largest painting on canvas in privat=
e hands; Palmieri=E2=80=99s clients had the largest work on paper. <br/></t=
d>
