          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">If Rotter=E2=80=99s=
 bidder, widely gossiped about and reported without contradiction as billio=
naire <b>Ken Griffin</b>, was also the third-party guarantor, the selling p=
rice was probably somewhere below the pro forma $121 million a non-guaranto=
r would have paid. (Christie=E2=80=99s no longer reports net prices, as Sot=
heby=E2=80=99s continues to do.) Nevertheless, the value statement had been=
 made. The top price for a Magritte had moved up by<i> 50 percent</i> in tw=
o and a half years, repricing almost everything underneath. A few lots afte=
r the gouache of <i>L=E2=80=99empire des lumi=C3=A8res</i>, a slightly smal=
ler gouache of a different Magritte image, <i>La recherche de l=E2=80=99abs=
olu, </i>estimated at $3 million, made $8.4 million with fees. By contrast,=
 two other Magrittes owned by Ertegun, which sold at the beginning of her s=
ale, only made prices around the estimate levels.
There was no Magritte bidding bump before the big <i>L=E2=80=99empire</i> p=
ainting sold. There was one after. Timing really is <i>everything</i>.<br/>=
<br/>Christie=E2=80=99s had carefully placed the Ertegun <i>L=E2=80=99empir=
e des lumi=C3=A8res </i>as the last lot, a fitting crescendo to her dedicat=
ed sale, but selling the gouache required an assist. The hope was that the =
underbidder on the large painting would switch to the smaller one, but brui=
sed feelings take a little time to get over, and Christie=E2=80=99s would h=
ave wanted a little space for the impact of the big sale to sink in. Also, =
if the big painting sold to the guarantor in an anticlimactic moment, the c=
hange of sale from Ertegun to various owners would act as a buffer, allowin=
g bidders to regroup and rebuild momentum. <br/><br/>In the end, there were=
 five lots placed between the big Magritte and its little brother, but the =
gouache was positioned right before Christie=E2=80=99s other big lot of the=
 evening: Ed Ruscha=E2=80=99s <i>Standard Station,
</i>priced at $50 million but expected to be bid higher. In setting up the =
lot order, Christie=E2=80=99s both expressed its confidence in its ability =
to market both paintings and put all of its eggs into one high-risk basket.=
 The big Magritte had a belt-and-suspenders third-party guarantee, but the =
small Magritte and the Ruscha were being sold naked, as they say. Both the =
little Magritte and the big Ruscha had to sell well for Christie=E2=80=99s =
to call the night a success=E2=80=94and make any money. <br/><br/>In the en=
d, Christie=E2=80=99s didn=E2=80=99t have to worry. Close to a dozen differ=
ent bidders chased the <i>L=E2=80=99empire</i> gouache. Bidding started in =
the room for as little as $4.8 million, but quickly escalated in a relay ra=
ce of bidding and counter-bidding. <b>Max Carter</b>, who had done so much =
to carry the ball on Palmieri=E2=80=99s consignment in-house, came in at $1=
1 million. There were still several bidders active at $14 million, but Li-C=
ohen=E2=80=94who=E2=80=99d come in at $12.5 million, presumably
representing the under bidder on the big empire painting=E2=80=94pushed to =
$15.5 million. Carter took one last shot, chopping his bid to $15.7 million=
, which signalled to Li-Cohen that $16 million would most likely take it. S=
he bid that=E2=80=A6 and won. <br/><br/>Art auctions rarely adhere to such =
a tightly choreographed and cinematic script. Minutes before the sale, <b>M=
ichel Legrand</b>=E2=80=99s theme to <i>The Thomas Crown Affair</i> came ov=
er the sound system, in homage to a Magritte having been the object of Crow=
n=E2=80=99s larcenous obsession in the 1999 remake. The sale of the gouache=
 provided the necessary subplot to bring the whole story together. <br/></t=
d>
